snippet.textDisplay: The EVGA 7800 GTX KO (the last time the KO naming was used) wasn't an exit strategy for the 7800 GTX GPU. In fact not only did it release a short 3 months after the launch of the 7800 GTX, but it also sported a newly designed heatsink and a higher factory OC compared to the launch version. Sort of like an early version of the FTW or SC naming. And then 3 months after that, the 7800 GTX 512mb was launched. Same GPU, but it was clocked higher, added more/faster memory, and a dual slot cooler to better handle the higher heat output.

snippet.textDisplay:
They actually pushed out new firmware that applies a base-line overclock that improves performance 10-20%.

So the good news, bad news and mystifying news. Good: Performance boost! Bad: Not all cards will be shipped with this latest firmware applied. Mystifying: Why would they push some cards out with slower firmware and some with better firmware? Note this isn't drivers, this is actual firmware. And how many people are going to end up with hampered performance without ever knowing?

snippet.textDisplay: who the hell is still gaming at 1080p? I started gaming in 2004 with a 6 set up (running quad crossfire AMD), then when all those monitors died I switched to a single 27" 1440p. Still Running AMD, now I'm on a q60r gaming tv with a rx vega 64 and as long as I don't max the setting I get 400+ frames a second. The key to getting high fps is turning vsinc off. Pretty easy. And instead of ultra setting I turn all the toggles down just one notch. (just one notch) and I get 150fps in almost all modern games. Games like strange brigade, guns and canolli, dirt 4 all get 400fps and way more.
